{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535817"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:59:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:59:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15521"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15521"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.07,0.06,0.67,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8212"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61733"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8212"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15521"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47179"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"16"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5394"},{"type":"tags","id":"9585"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19867"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61733"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic requesting advice about a new medication for osteoporosis prevention. A recent randomised controlled trial compared this medication to placebo over three years. In the treatment group, 30 of 1000 participants experienced a fracture. In the placebo group, 50 of 1000 participants experienced a fracture.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the absolute risk reduction for fractures with this medication?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["0.40","0.03","0.05","0.02","0.50"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question tests understanding of absolute risk reduction (ARR), a key measure of treatment effect in clinical trials. Let\u0027s organise the data into a two-by-two table:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cdiv class=\u0022table-container\u0022\u003E\u003Ctable border=\u00221\u0022 style=\u0022border-collapse:collapse;margin:10px 0;\u0022\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EFracture\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003ENo Fracture\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003ETotal\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ETreatment\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E30\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E970\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E1000\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EPlacebo\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E50\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E950\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E1000\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/table\u003E\u003C/div\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0.02\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer. The absolute risk reduction is calculated by subtracting the event rate in the treatment group from the event rate in the control group:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EControl event rate = 50/1000 = 0.05\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment event rate = 30/1000 = 0.03\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EARR = 0.05 - 0.03 = 0.02 or 2%\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0.03\u003C/strong\u003E represents the event rate in the treatment group, not the absolute risk reduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0.05\u003C/strong\u003E represents the event rate in the control group, not the absolute risk reduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0.40\u003C/strong\u003E represents the relative risk reduction (calculated as ARR/control event rate = 0.02/0.05 = 0.40 or 40%), not the absolute risk reduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0.50\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest a much larger treatment effect than what was observed in this trial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Number Needed to Treat (NNT) can be calculated as 1/ARR = 1/0.02 = 50, meaning we need to treat 50 patients to prevent one fracture over three years.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Absolute risk reduction (ARR) is calculated by subtracting the event rate in the treatment group from the event rate in the control group.","Number needed to treat (NNT) is the reciprocal of the absolute risk reduction.","Two-by-two contingency tables are useful tools for calculating risk measures in clinical trials."],"references":["Talluri SK. Relative risk reduction and absolute risk reduction. BMJ. 2009 Sep 16;339:b3626."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47179"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15521"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47179"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-16T11:42:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-16T11:43:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8212"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61733"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"16","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/16"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"dat